{"title_page": "Siv Jensen", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Siv Jensen\n|honorific-suffix  = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n|image         = Siv Jensen-14.jpg\n|caption =\n|office        =  [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]]\n|primeminister = [[Erna Solberg]]\n|term_start    = 16 October 2013\n|term_end      = 24 January 2020\n|predecessor   = [[Sigbj\u00f8rn Johnsen]]\n|successor     = [[Jan Tore Sanner]]\n|office1       = [[Progress Party (Norway)|Leader of the Progress Party]]\n| deputy1= [[Per Sandberg]] (First Deputy; 2006&ndash;2018) <br/> [[Sylvi Listhaug]] (First Deputy; 2018&ndash;) <br/> [[Per Arne Olsen]] (Second Deputy; 2005&ndash;2013)<br>[[Ketil Solvik-Olsen]] (Second Deputy; 2013&ndash;2019) <br/> [[Terje S\u00f8viknes]] (Second Deputy; 2019&ndash;)\n|term_start1   = 6 May 2006\n|term_end1     = \n|predecessor1  = [[Carl I. Hagen]]\n|successor1    = \n|office2= [[Deputy Leader|First Deputy Leader of the]] [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]]\n|term_start2= 2 May 1999\n|term_end2= 6 May 2006\n|leader2= [[Carl I. Hagen]]\n|predecessor2= [[Lodve Solholm]]\n|successor2= [[Per Sandberg]] \n|office3= [[Parliament|Parliamentary Leader]] [[Progress Party (Norway)|of the Progress Party]]\n|term_start3= 28 January 2020\n|term_end3= \n|leader3= Herself \n|predecessor3= [[Hans Andreas Limi]]\n|successor3= \n|term_start4= 5 October 2005\n|term_end4= 17 October 2013\n|leader4= Carl I. Hagen <br/> Herself\n|predecessor4= [[Carl I. Hagen]]\n|successor4= [[Harald T. Nesvik|Harald Tom Nesvik]]\n|office5= [[Storting|Member of the Norwegian Parliament]]\n|term_start5   = 1 October 1997\n|term_end5    =\n|constituency5 = [[Oslo]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1969|06|01|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]]\n|alma_mater    = [[Norwegian School of Economics|Norwegian School of<br />Economics]]\n|religion      = [[Church of Norway|Lutheranism]]\n}}\n'''Siv Jensen''' (born 1 June 1969) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] politician and leader of the [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]] since 2006. She also held the position as [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]] from 2013 to 2020 in the [[Solberg Cabinet]]. She has been a member of the [[Storting|Norwegian parliament]] from [[Oslo]] since 1997.\n\nBorn and raised in Oslo, Jensen graduated with a degree in business studies from the [[Norwegian School of Economics]]. She was first elected to parliament in the [[1997 Norwegian parliamentary election|1997 parliamentary election]], and has later been re-elected for four consecutive terms. She chaired the parliamentary [[Standing Committee on Finance and Economic Affairs]] from 2001 to 2005, and in 2006 succeeded long-time chairman [[Carl I. Hagen]] as leader of the Progress Party.\n\nJensen was the Progress Party's candidate for [[Prime Minister of Norway|Prime Minister]] in the [[2009 Norwegian parliamentary election|2009 parliamentary election]], which saw record high results for the party. For the [[2013 Norwegian parliamentary election|2013 parliamentary election]] she supported prospects of a coalition government headed by the [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative Party]], and led her party into the [[Solberg's Cabinet|Solberg Cabinet]], the Progress Party's first ever government participation.\n\nJensen became Norway's longest-serving Minister of Finance since World War II in October 2019.<ref>https://www.tv2.no/a/10900947/</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSiv Jensen was born in [[Oslo]] to [[self-employment|self-employed]] Tore Jensen (1926\u20131989), and Monica Kjelsberg (born 1939),<ref name=stort>{{cite web|url=http://www.stortinget.no/no/Representanter-og-komiteer/Representantene/Representantfordeling/Representant/?perid=SIVJ|title=Jensen, Siv (1969-)|work=Stortinget.no|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> owners of a shoe store during her childhood. While she holds that her [[neighbourhood]] was a nice place to grow up, her home was the scene of numerous [[burglary|burglaries]].<ref name=db20505>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/magasinet/2005/05/02/430472.html|work=[[Dagbladet]]|title=Under panseret|first=Ingvild Wedaa|last=Tennfjord|date=2 May 2005|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Her parents were divorced around 1980,<ref name=db011201>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/tekstarkiv/artikkel.php?id=5001010065841&tag=item&words=vidar%3Bkleppe|work=[[Dagbladet]]|title=P\u00e5 mors parti|first=Thomas|last=Ergo|date=1 December 2001|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> and her father soon moved to [[Sweden]].<ref name=snl>{{cite web|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Siv_Jensen/utdypning|title=Siv Jensen|work=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Lise Merete|last=Olaussen|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Her mother was for a short while active in the [[Ullern]] Progress Party, until finding out that politics was \"not her thing\".<ref name=hh>''Hele Historien: Siv Jensen'' (9 November 2006). [[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]].</ref>\n\nAfter completing Marienlyst elementary school in 1985, Jensen attended upper secondary school at [[Oslo Commerce School]] in Oslo's [[Frogner]] district, graduating in 1988. Afterwards she enrolled in the [[Norwegian School of Economics]], receiving her degree in business studies in 1992.<ref name=stort/> She worked as a sales consultant for ''Radio 1'' from 1992, until dedicating her professional life to politics full-time in 1994.<ref name=\"storenorske\"/>\n\nHer political interest was according to herself sparked at her elementary school Marienlyst where discussions were common in class. These discussions would include two students who were members of the [[Socialist Youth (Norway)|Socialist Youth]], one being her socialist-turned best friend.<ref name=snl/> Jensen however soon found herself strongly opposed to their views.<ref name=p4port/> She joined the Progress Party in 1988,<ref name=snl/> in part having been introduced to the party through her mother.<ref name=hh/> Sometime before joining the party, she had briefly been a member of the [[Norwegian Young Conservatives|Young Conservatives]], for about a week.<ref name=snl/><ref name=p4port/>\n\n==Political career==\n\n=== Member of Parliament ===\nJensen has been a member of the [[Storting]] from the Oslo constituency since first being elected in 1997, while having served as a deputy representative from 1993 to 1997. As she was appointed to the government cabinet in 2013, deputy representative [[Mazyar Keshvari]] has met as a regular member in her place.<ref name=stort/> From 2001 to 2005 Jensen chaired the [[Standing Committee on Finance and Economic Affairs]], having been a member of the committee since 1997, and from 2005 to 2013 she was a member of the [[Standing Committee on Foreign Affairs and Defence]].<ref>[http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/fin/the-ministry/minister-of-finance-siv-jensen.html?id=742945 Minister of Finance Siv Jensen (Progress Party)], ''Ministry of Finance''</ref> She played a central role in budget negotiations with the centrist government of [[Kjell Magne Bondevik]], and her work chairing the Finance Committee led her to become increasingly more profiled as a leader-figure within her party.<ref name=\"storenorske\"/>\n\n===Party leadership===\n[[File:Siv_Jensen,_partiledare_Fremskrittspartiet_Norge,_talar_under_Nordiska_radets_session_i_Kopehamn_2006.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Siv Jensen in 2006.]]\n[[File:Valg 2009 029.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Siv Jensen speaking at a rally in [[Oslo]] in the 2009 electoral campaign.]]\n[[File:Siv_Jensen_debatterar_under_Nordiska_radets_session_i_Stockholm_2009.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Siv Jensen in Stockholm, Sweden, 2009.]]\n[[File:Jens_Stoltenberg_och_Siv_Jensen._Nordiska_radets_session_i_Stockholm_2009.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Jensen with former Prime Minister [[Jens Stoltenberg]].]]\nDuring the early 1990s conflict within the party between the younger libertarians and party chairman [[Carl I. Hagen]], Jensen stood on the side of Hagen.<ref name=snl/> She also supported Hagen in the 2001 internal conflict, and stated the same year that Hagen had been like a father figure for her.<ref name=db011201/> She became first deputy chairman of the Progress Party in 1998, and parliamentary leader of the party in 2005. In 2006, Carl I. Hagen, chairman of the party since 1978 resigned to become vice president of parliament, and Jensen assumed leadership of the Progress Party to no internal opposition.<ref name=\"storenorske\">[https://snl.no/Siv_Jensen \"Siv Jensen\"], ''Store norske leksikon'', 3.11.2013</ref> While many had been speculating about the viability of the party and its future after Hagen resigning, a 2004 survey showed that Jensen enjoyed better general support than him, which was explained by her not being as controversial.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dn.no/forsiden/politikkSamfunn/article399445.ece|title=Siv Jensen danker ut Hagen|work=[[Dagens N\u00e6ringsliv]]|date=21 December 2004|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Many had also predicted a more moderate course for the party with her being the leader, but she stood firmly by the policies of the party.<ref name=snl/> Her leadership-style has however been considered to be softer than that of Hagen.<ref name=\"storenorske\"/>\n\nIn May 2009, Jensen held a lecture in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom]] at the invitation of [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] MP [[Malcolm Rifkind]]. Media director Alex Try of the [[think tank]] [[Henry Jackson Society]], who was responsible for the arrangement, said that the main background for the invitation was her \"engagement in questions about terrorism and challenges attached to the multicultural society.\" Up to one-hundred MP's, business leaders and key persons in British politics was expected to show up at the arrangement. Jensen said that \"we have much to learn from the British, but when it comes to the immigration policy I think Britain has failed completely\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.frp.no/Siv+Jensen+holder+foredrag+for+ledere+i+britisk+politikk+og+n%C3%A6ringsliv.d25-TgZbK3j.ips|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904122904/http://www.frp.no/Siv+Jensen+holder+foredrag+for+ledere+i+britisk+politikk+og+n%C3%A6ringsliv.d25-TgZbK3j.ips|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 September 2009|title=Siv Jensen holder foredrag for ledere i britisk politikk og n\u00e6ringsliv|work=[[Progress Party (Norway)|Frp.no]]|date=8 May 2009|first=Camilla|last=Mollatt|authorlink=Camilla Mollatt|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nAs leader of the Progress Party, Jensen took the initiative to talks with Conservative Party leader [[Erna Solberg]] in early 2007, seeking to build a broad centre-right coalition for the 2009 election.<ref name=snl/> Amid unresolved dispute among the centre-right parties,<ref>[http://www.abcnyheter.no/nyheter/politikk/090120/frp-mot-full-isolasjon \"Frp mot full isolasjon\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218053649/http://www.abcnyheter.no/nyheter/politikk/090120/frp-mot-full-isolasjon |date=18 December 2014 }}, ''ABC Nyheter/NTB'', 20.01.2009</ref> she launched herself as candidate for Prime Minister for the 2009 election and received a record share of the vote of 22.9%, although the parties combined ultimately lost out to the centre-left coalition.<ref name=\"storenorske\"/>\n\nIn 2011, newspaper ''[[Aftenposten]]'' wrote that the Progress Party during Jensen's leadership, had experienced their \"two best national elections\".<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]]|date=17 November 2011|quote=I den virkelige verden har Frp under Siv Jensen gjort sine beste valg gjennom historien.}}</ref> Ahead of the 2013 election Jensen continued working for a broad centre-right coalition, and endorsed [[Erna Solberg]] for Prime Minister. Although seeing its vote drop significantly, she led the Progress Party into government coalition talks for the first time in its history.<ref name=\"storenorske\"/>\n\n===Minister of Finance===\nOn 16 October 2013 Jensen was appointed Minister of Finance as the Progress Party joined a minority coalition government led by the Conservative Party, the party's first ever government participation.<ref>Saleha Mohsin, [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-10-16/norway-names-jensen-finance-minister-after-oil-spending-accord.html \"Norway Names Jensen Finance Minister After Oil Spending Deal\"], ''Bloomberg'', Oct 16, 2013</ref> Jensen's first national budget included proposals of cutting taxes, and spending more of Norway's oil wealth, and she also appointed a committee to consider changes to the 4% [[The budgetary rule|budgetary rule]] of [[Government Pension Fund of Norway|Oil Fund]] spending.<ref>[https://online.wsj.com/articles/norway-to-spend-more-oil-wealth-cut-taxes-1412766630 \"Norway to Spend More Oil Wealth, Cut Taxes\"], ''Wall Street Journal'', Oct. 8, 2014</ref>\n\n==Political views==\n\n===Economy===\nJensen has described her party to be a \"classical liberal party and also a very democratic party\", and that its \"basic main focus areas are individual freedom, individual rights, less state and more individual freedom\", also that the party is \"in favor of more competition instead of less. Because we fight state monopolies because they don't do good for competition, for price levels, for people's ability to choose between different distributors. That's our basic ideology behind the party\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/interview_norway_progress_party_leader_rejects_anti-muslim_label/24279650.html|work=Radio Free Europe|title= Interview: Norwegian Party Leader Rejects 'Anti-Muslim' Label|date=28 July 2011 |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nHaving been called a \"Norwegian Margaret Thatcher\" in the British press, Jensen has said she views former [[British Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]] as one of her \"political heroes\".<ref name=standp/> Considering Thatcher \"a controversial politician who dared to stand for something,\" Jensen has expressed support for [[Thatcherism|Thatcherite]] policies such as \"[[there is no alternative]] (to [[market economy]])\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2009/05/07/nyheter/inneriks/politikk/regjeringen/siv_jensen/6110686/|title=Norges nye jernlady|first=Gunnar|last=Thorenfeldt|date=7 May 2009|work=[[Dagbladet]]|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\n[[File:S_Jensen_02.jpg|thumb|left|220px]]\n[[File:Sivjensenogfpu.jpg|thumb|Siv Jensen speaking before a [[Progress Party\u2019s Youth (Norway)|Progress Party\u2019s Youth]] summer camp.]]\nJensen is a staunch supporter of [[Israel]], and has stated that she is \"not afraid to defend Israel's right to defend itself.\" She visited the Israeli city of [[Sderot]] in the summer of 2008 and experienced [[Hamas]] bombing first hand, forcing her and her company to run for the air-raid shelter. She strongly opposed the Norwegian government's decision to recognise Hamas as she holds that \"you don't negotiate with terrorists, you just don't.\"<ref name=standp>{{cite news|url=http://www.standpointmag.co.uk/node/692/full|title=A Norwegian Thatcher?|work=[[Standpoint (magazine)|Standpoint]]|date=December 2008|authorlink=Bruce Bawer|first=Bruce|last=Bawer|accessdate=21 December 2010}}</ref> Jensen has in addition advocated [[Positions on Jerusalem|moving the Norwegian embassy in Israel]] from [[Tel Aviv]] to [[Jerusalem]], while also being open to accepting a future recognition of a [[State of Palestine|Palestinian state]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=529145|work=[[Verdens Gang]] (NTB)|date=27 August 2008|title=Jensen vil flytte norsk ambassade til Jerusalem|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, in light of the [[Gaza War (2008\u201309)|Gaza War]], she held an appeal at a demonstration called \"Let Israel live\" in support of Israel in Oslo. The Progress Party's general Israel-policy, supported by the appearance at the demonstration by Jensen and the fact that [[Christian Democratic Party (Norway)|Christian Democratic Party]] leader [[Dagfinn H\u00f8ybr\u00e5ten]] had not joined the demonstration, resulted in many Christian Democratic voters turning to the Progress Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tv2nyhetene.no/innenriks/politikk/valg09/-israels-krigfoering-var-ogsaa-terror-2884507.html|title=- Israels krigf\u00f8ring var ogs\u00e5 terror|work=[[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]]|date=1 September 2009|first=Eivind|last=Fondenes|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Soon after, the [[Norwegian Police Security Service]] (PST) went public, fearing that Jensen might be the target of attacks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=539656|title=Politiet frykter angrep p\u00e5 Siv Jensen |work=[[Verdens Gang]]|date=8 January 2009|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> During the speech, which was held amid the [[2008\u201309 Oslo riots]], Jensen and pro-Israel demonstrators were suddenly attacked by violent rioters throwing rocks, and Jensen was forced to leave the podium.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/midtosten/artikkel.php?artid=545854 |title=Politiet bruker t\u00e5regass mot demonstranter  |work=Verdens Gang |date=8 January 2009 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\n===Radical Islam===\nIn February 2009, Jensen held a speech where she warned about what she called a \"sneaking Islamisation\" (''snikislamisering'') of Norway on the background of a public debate about allowing [[hijab]] as part of the police uniform, and demands from Muslim groups of Muslim-only education and special food in prisons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2009/02/21/nyheter/politikk/innenriks/frp/siv_jensen/4966977/|title=Siv Jensen advarer mot snikislamisering|work=[[Dagbladet]]|date=21 February 2009|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> The speech turned out to be highly controversial in the other parties.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=547178|title=Vil stenge Siv ute fra innvandringsdebatten|work=[[Verdens Gang]]|date=23 February 2009|first=Kathrine|last=Hammerstad|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/1.6493505|title=- Sivs beskrivelse er langt fra sann|work=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=23 February 2009|first1=Bj\u00f8rn|last1=Myklebust|first2=Kristine Grue|last2=Langset|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> She used the immigrant-heavy [[Malm\u00f6]], [[Sweden]] city district of [[Roseng\u00e5rd]] to illustrate failed integration policies, claiming that [[Sharia law]] had replaced Swedish law and that emergency staff could not drive into certain areas. The statements proved highly controversial in Sweden, and the Progress Party was invited to a tour around Roseng\u00e5rd by the mayor and police chief of Malm\u00f6, which it accepted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=547220|title=Politisjefen i Roseng\u00e5rd \"arresterer\" Siv Jensen - Svensk lov gjelder i Roseng\u00e5rd|work=[[Verdens Gang]]|date=23 February 2009|first=Bj\u00f8rnar|last=Tommelstad|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagsavisen.no/innenriks/article400282.ece|title=\u00d8nsker Frp velkommen til Roseng\u00e5rd|work=[[Dagsavisen]]|date=24 February 2009|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100809112716/http://www.dagsavisen.no/innenriks/article400282.ece|archivedate=9 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Jensen did however not join the tour herself.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nettavisen.no/innenriks/politikk/article2569815.ece|title=Jensen st\u00e5r over Sverige-tur|work=[[Nettavisen]]|date=9 March 2009|first1=Trond|last1=Lepper\u00f8d|first2=Heidi Schei|last2=Lille\u00e5s|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nFurther, in March 2009, she stated that the fight against [[radical Islam]] \"is the most important fight of our time.\" She said that she, as a classical liberal, would always fight against totalitarian ideas such as [[communism]] and [[nazism]], and that radical Islam \"is a dark and scary ideology.\" She also accused the other parties of being cowardly, ignoring the questions raised by the Progress Party, and claimed that \"it is probably an expression of the fact that they don't understand what's happening in society around them. They close their eyes and try to present themselves as tolerant and liberal, when in fact they are deeply intolerant.\"<ref name=dag23>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2009/03/02/nyheter/innenriks/politikk/siv_jensen/islam/5100011/|title=- Kampen mot radikal islam er v\u00e5r tids viktigste|work=[[Dagbladet]]|first=Arnhild Aass|last=Kristiansen|date=2 March 2009|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Both these controversies resulted in large popular gains for the Progress Party in polls.<ref name=dag23/> In response to an incident in early 2010, where thousands of Muslims demonstrated in Oslo, she changed her claim of a \"sneak-Islamisation\" of Norway, to instead claim that the debate now was of a full-blown [[Islamisation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/article3515805.ece|work=[[Aftenposten]]|title=Frykter \u00e5pen islamisering|date=13 February 2010|first=Gunnar|last=Magnus|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629123913/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/article3515805.ece|archivedate=29 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrk.no/nett-tv/nyheter/spill/verdi/123458/|title=Siv Jensens tordentale|work=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}} (Video clip)</ref> During the demonstration (a response to newspaper ''[[Dagbladet]]'' publishing a [[Muhammad]] cartoon in the context of a news story) Islamist [[Mohyeldeen Mohammad]] had notably \"warned\" of a \"[[September 11 attacks|9/11]]\" or \"[[7 July 2005 London bombings|7/7]]\" in Norway to applause from the crowd.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2010/02/12/nyheter/karikatur/utenriks/politikk/innenriks/10369255/|title=Advarte mot 11. september i Norge|work=[[Dagbladet]]|date=12 February 2010|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\n===Climate change===\nAbout [[climate change]], Jensen said in December 2008 that \"we can see that climate changes are happening, but they have been happening for as long as the world has existed. The question is whether they are man-made or not, or whether they are dangerous or not. Just some 30 years ago, all these scientists said that the world was getting colder, and now they have changed their mind and say that the world is getting warmer. So is that what's happening, or isn't it?\" Regardless, she is largely supportive of expanding and researching into renewable energy production.<ref name=standp/> In January 2010 she attacked the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change|IPCC]], accusing the report from the panel of being based on fraudulent data. She referred to the erroneous statement of [[Himalaya]]n [[glacier]]s melting by 2035, ice melting predictions by [[Al Gore]] and [[Jonas Gahr St\u00f8re]], questions of [[Sampling (statistics)|statistical sampling]], and emails from climate scientists at the [[Climatic Research Unit email incident|Climatic Research Unit]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/article3493769.ece|work=[[Aftenposten]]|title=- Ikke mer snakk om global oppvarming|first=Gunnar Magnus Paul|last=Audestad|date=31 January 2010|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604034803/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/article3493769.ece|archivedate=4 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nBesides three half-sisters,<ref name=p4port>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/p4-portrettet/id303308158|work=[[P4 Radio Hele Norge|P4]]|title=Portrettet: Siv Jensen|date=1 March 2009|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Jensen has one younger brother, businessman Tom Einar Jensen,<ref>{{cite news|last=Online|first=Hegnar|title=Jensen gikk p\u00e5 dagen|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2013/09/13/nyheter/okonomi/hegnarno/agrinos/bohn/29247873/|accessdate=13 September 2013|newspaper=Dagbladet.no|date=13 September 2013|language=Norwegian}}</ref> and one younger sister, Nina Jensen, former CEO of [[World Wide Fund for Nature|WWF]].<ref name=\"storenorske\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=165531|title=Frp-Siv f\u00e5r milj\u00f8kjeft fra lilles\u00f8ster|work=[[Verdens Gang]]|first=Line|last=Torvik|date=27 January 2007|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Norway. Her great-grandmother was the early [[feminist movement|feminist]] [[Betzy Kjelsberg]].<ref name=tu>{{cite news|url=http://www.tu.no/politikk/article187822.ece|title=FrP-Siv vil lykkes innen 2013|work=[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]|first=Tormod|last=Haugstad|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian|date=18 November 2008}}</ref> Although she was once engaged, Jensen has never married.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nilsen|first=Per Ingar|title=Siv Jensen snakker ut om bruddet   Br\u00f8t forlovelse med dr\u00f8mmemannen|url=http://www.klikk.no/produkthjemmesider/herogna/article857664.ece|accessdate=14 September 2013|newspaper=Her og N\u00e5|date=23 August 2013|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nJensen has stated to be a \"proud member of the [[Church of Norway]]\", while expressing some personal doubt about certain Christian doctrines. She has criticised church leaders for getting too involved in politics, particularly in regard to some church leaders publicly voicing opposition to Norwegian [[oil drilling]].<ref>[http://e24.no/kommentarer/spaltister/oljesoel-fra-kirken/2937998 \"Oljes\u00f8l fra Kirken\"], ''E24'', 20.02.2009</ref><ref>[http://www.vl.no/2.627/en-varslet-katastrofe-1.61098 \"En varslet katastrofe\"], ''V\u00e5rt Land'', 30.08.2013</ref>\n\nIn 2006, a biography on Siv Jensen was released, written by Martine Aurdal, chief editor of the feminist magazine ''Fett'', later chief editor of the [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] news magazine ''[[Ny Tid]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.klassekampen.no/39923/article/item/null|title=Avviser drahjelp til Frp|work=[[Klassekampen]]|date=4 October 2006|first=Christiane Jordheim|last=Larsen|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717135407/http://www.klassekampen.no/39923/article/item/null|archivedate=17 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|title=Siv: Portrett av en formann|first=Martine|last=Aurdal|year=2006|publisher=Kagge forlag|location=Oslo}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Carl I. Hagen|Carl Hagen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]]|years=2006\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sigbj\u00f8rn Johnsen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]]|years=2013\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jan Tore Sanner]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Stortinget 2001-2005}}\n{{stortinget 2005-2009}}\n{{Stortinget 2009-2013}}\n{{Stortinget 2013-2017}}\n{{Stortinget 2017-2021}}\n{{Progress Party (Norway)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jensen, Siv}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Norwegian Lutherans]]\n[[Category:Norwegian School of Economics alumni]]\n[[Category:Progress Party (Norway) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Storting]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Norway]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Finance of Norway]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Storting]]\n[[Category:Critics of Islamism]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian women politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Norway]]\n[[Category:Women finance ministers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Siv Jensen\n|honorific-suffix  = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n|image         = Siv Jensen-14.jpg\n|caption =\n|office        =  [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]]\n|primeminister = [[Erna Solberg]]\n|term_start    = 16 October 2013\n|term_end      = 24 January 2020\n|predecessor   = [[Sigbj\u00f8rn Johnsen]]\n|successor     = [[Jan Tore Sanner]]\n|office1       = [[Progress Party (Norway)|Leader of the Progress Party]]\n| deputy1= [[Per Sandberg]] (First Deputy; 2006&ndash;2018) <br/> [[Sylvi Listhaug]] (First Deputy; 2018&ndash;) <br/> [[Per Arne Olsen]] (Second Deputy; 2005&ndash;2013)<br>[[Ketil Solvik-Olsen]] (Second Deputy; 2013&ndash;2019) <br/> [[Terje S\u00f8viknes]] (Second Deputy; 2019&ndash;)\n|term_start1   = 6 May 2006\n|term_end1     = \n|predecessor1  = [[Carl I. Hagen]]\n|successor1    = \n|office2= [[Deputy Leader|First Deputy Leader of the]] [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]]\n|term_start2= 2 May 1999\n|term_end2= 6 May 2006\n|leader2= [[Carl I. Hagen]]\n|predecessor2= [[Lodve Solholm]]\n|successor2= [[Per Sandberg]] \n|office3= [[Parliament|Parlimentary Leader]] [[Progress Party (Norway)|of the Progress Party]]\n|term_start3= 28 January 2020\n|term_end3= \n|leader3= Herself \n|predecessor3= [[Hans Andreas Limi]]\n|successor3= \n|term_start4= 5 October 2005\n|term_end4= 17 October 2013\n|leader4= Carl I. Hagen <br/> Herself\n|predecessor4= [[Carl I. Hagen]]\n|successor4= [[Harald T. Nesvik|Harald Tom Nesvik]]\n|office5= [[Storting|Member of the Norwegian Parliament]]\n|term_start5   = 1 October 1997\n|term_end5    =\n|constituency5 = [[Oslo]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1969|06|01|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]]\n|alma_mater    = [[Norwegian School of Economics|Norwegian School of<br />Economics]]\n|religion      = [[Church of Norway|Lutheranism]]\n}}\n'''Siv Jensen''' (born 1 June 1969) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] politician and leader of the [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]] since 2006. She also held the position as [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]] from 2013 to 2020 in the [[Solberg Cabinet]]. She has been a member of the [[Storting|Norwegian parliament]] from [[Oslo]] since 1997.\n\nBorn and raised in Oslo, Jensen graduated with a degree in business studies from the [[Norwegian School of Economics]]. She was first elected to parliament in the [[1997 Norwegian parliamentary election|1997 parliamentary election]], and has later been re-elected for four consecutive terms. She chaired the parliamentary [[Standing Committee on Finance and Economic Affairs]] from 2001 to 2005, and in 2006 succeeded long-time chairman [[Carl I. Hagen]] as leader of the Progress Party.\n\nJensen was the Progress Party's candidate for [[Prime Minister of Norway|Prime Minister]] in the [[2009 Norwegian parliamentary election|2009 parliamentary election]], which saw record high results for the party. For the [[2013 Norwegian parliamentary election|2013 parliamentary election]] she supported prospects of a coalition government headed by the [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative Party]], and led her party into the [[Solberg's Cabinet|Solberg Cabinet]], the Progress Party's first ever government participation.\n\nJensen became Norway's longest-serving Minister of Finance since World War II in October 2019.<ref>https://www.tv2.no/a/10900947/</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSiv Jensen was born in [[Oslo]] to [[self-employment|self-employed]] Tore Jensen (1926\u20131989), and Monica Kjelsberg (born 1939),<ref name=stort>{{cite web|url=http://www.stortinget.no/no/Representanter-og-komiteer/Representantene/Representantfordeling/Representant/?perid=SIVJ|title=Jensen, Siv (1969-)|work=Stortinget.no|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> owners of a shoe store during her childhood. While she holds that her [[neighbourhood]] was a nice place to grow up, her home was the scene of numerous [[burglary|burglaries]].<ref name=db20505>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/magasinet/2005/05/02/430472.html|work=[[Dagbladet]]|title=Under panseret|first=Ingvild Wedaa|last=Tennfjord|date=2 May 2005|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Her parents were divorced around 1980,<ref name=db011201>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/tekstarkiv/artikkel.php?id=5001010065841&tag=item&words=vidar%3Bkleppe|work=[[Dagbladet]]|title=P\u00e5 mors parti|first=Thomas|last=Ergo|date=1 December 2001|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> and her father soon moved to [[Sweden]].<ref name=snl>{{cite web|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Siv_Jensen/utdypning|title=Siv Jensen|work=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Lise Merete|last=Olaussen|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Her mother was for a short while active in the [[Ullern]] Progress Party, until finding out that politics was \"not her thing\".<ref name=hh>''Hele Historien: Siv Jensen'' (9 November 2006). [[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]].</ref>\n\nAfter completing Marienlyst elementary school in 1985, Jensen attended upper secondary school at [[Oslo Commerce School]] in Oslo's [[Frogner]] district, graduating in 1988. Afterwards she enrolled in the [[Norwegian School of Economics]], receiving her degree in business studies in 1992.<ref name=stort/> She worked as a sales consultant for ''Radio 1'' from 1992, until dedicating her professional life to politics full-time in 1994.<ref name=\"storenorske\"/>\n\nHer political interest was according to herself sparked at her elementary school Marienlyst where discussions were common in class. These discussions would include two students who were members of the [[Socialist Youth (Norway)|Socialist Youth]], one being her socialist-turned best friend.<ref name=snl/> Jensen however soon found herself strongly opposed to their views.<ref name=p4port/> She joined the Progress Party in 1988,<ref name=snl/> in part having been introduced to the party through her mother.<ref name=hh/> Sometime before joining the party, she had briefly been a member of the [[Norwegian Young Conservatives|Young Conservatives]], for about a week.<ref name=snl/><ref name=p4port/>\n\n==Political career==\n\n=== Member of Parliament ===\nJensen has been a member of the [[Storting]] from the Oslo constituency since first being elected in 1997, while having served as a deputy representative from 1993 to 1997. As she was appointed to the government cabinet in 2013, deputy representative [[Mazyar Keshvari]] has met as a regular member in her place.<ref name=stort/> From 2001 to 2005 Jensen chaired the [[Standing Committee on Finance and Economic Affairs]], having been a member of the committee since 1997, and from 2005 to 2013 she was a member of the [[Standing Committee on Foreign Affairs and Defence]].<ref>[http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/fin/the-ministry/minister-of-finance-siv-jensen.html?id=742945 Minister of Finance Siv Jensen (Progress Party)], ''Ministry of Finance''</ref> She played a central role in budget negotiations with the centrist government of [[Kjell Magne Bondevik]], and her work chairing the Finance Committee led her to become increasingly more profiled as a leader-figure within her party.<ref name=\"storenorske\"/>\n\n===Party leadership===\n[[File:Siv_Jensen,_partiledare_Fremskrittspartiet_Norge,_talar_under_Nordiska_radets_session_i_Kopehamn_2006.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Siv Jensen in 2006.]]\n[[File:Valg 2009 029.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Siv Jensen speaking at a rally in [[Oslo]] in the 2009 electoral campaign.]]\n[[File:Siv_Jensen_debatterar_under_Nordiska_radets_session_i_Stockholm_2009.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Siv Jensen in Stockholm, Sweden, 2009.]]\n[[File:Jens_Stoltenberg_och_Siv_Jensen._Nordiska_radets_session_i_Stockholm_2009.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Jensen with former Prime Minister [[Jens Stoltenberg]].]]\nDuring the early 1990s conflict within the party between the younger libertarians and party chairman [[Carl I. Hagen]], Jensen stood on the side of Hagen.<ref name=snl/> She also supported Hagen in the 2001 internal conflict, and stated the same year that Hagen had been like a father figure for her.<ref name=db011201/> She became first deputy chairman of the Progress Party in 1998, and parliamentary leader of the party in 2005. In 2006, Carl I. Hagen, chairman of the party since 1978 resigned to become vice president of parliament, and Jensen assumed leadership of the Progress Party to no internal opposition.<ref name=\"storenorske\">[https://snl.no/Siv_Jensen \"Siv Jensen\"], ''Store norske leksikon'', 3.11.2013</ref> While many had been speculating about the viability of the party and its future after Hagen resigning, a 2004 survey showed that Jensen enjoyed better general support than him, which was explained by her not being as controversial.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dn.no/forsiden/politikkSamfunn/article399445.ece|title=Siv Jensen danker ut Hagen|work=[[Dagens N\u00e6ringsliv]]|date=21 December 2004|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Many had also predicted a more moderate course for the party with her being the leader, but she stood firmly by the policies of the party.<ref name=snl/> Her leadership-style has however been considered to be softer than that of Hagen.<ref name=\"storenorske\"/>\n\nIn May 2009, Jensen held a lecture in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom]] at the invitation of [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] MP [[Malcolm Rifkind]]. Media director Alex Try of the [[think tank]] [[Henry Jackson Society]], who was responsible for the arrangement, said that the main background for the invitation was her \"engagement in questions about terrorism and challenges attached to the multicultural society.\" Up to one-hundred MP's, business leaders and key persons in British politics was expected to show up at the arrangement. Jensen said that \"we have much to learn from the British, but when it comes to the immigration policy I think Britain has failed completely\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.frp.no/Siv+Jensen+holder+foredrag+for+ledere+i+britisk+politikk+og+n%C3%A6ringsliv.d25-TgZbK3j.ips|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904122904/http://www.frp.no/Siv+Jensen+holder+foredrag+for+ledere+i+britisk+politikk+og+n%C3%A6ringsliv.d25-TgZbK3j.ips|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 September 2009|title=Siv Jensen holder foredrag for ledere i britisk politikk og n\u00e6ringsliv|work=[[Progress Party (Norway)|Frp.no]]|date=8 May 2009|first=Camilla|last=Mollatt|authorlink=Camilla Mollatt|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nAs leader of the Progress Party, Jensen took the initiative to talks with Conservative Party leader [[Erna Solberg]] in early 2007, seeking to build a broad centre-right coalition for the 2009 election.<ref name=snl/> Amid unresolved dispute among the centre-right parties,<ref>[http://www.abcnyheter.no/nyheter/politikk/090120/frp-mot-full-isolasjon \"Frp mot full isolasjon\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218053649/http://www.abcnyheter.no/nyheter/politikk/090120/frp-mot-full-isolasjon |date=18 December 2014 }}, ''ABC Nyheter/NTB'', 20.01.2009</ref> she launched herself as candidate for Prime Minister for the 2009 election and received a record share of the vote of 22.9%, although the parties combined ultimately lost out to the centre-left coalition.<ref name=\"storenorske\"/>\n\nIn 2011, newspaper ''[[Aftenposten]]'' wrote that the Progress Party during Jensen's leadership, had experienced their \"two best national elections\".<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Verdens Gang]]|date=17 November 2011|quote=I den virkelige verden har Frp under Siv Jensen gjort sine beste valg gjennom historien.}}</ref> Ahead of the 2013 election Jensen continued working for a broad centre-right coalition, and endorsed [[Erna Solberg]] for Prime Minister. Although seeing its vote drop significantly, she led the Progress Party into government coalition talks for the first time in its history.<ref name=\"storenorske\"/>\n\n===Minister of Finance===\nOn 16 October 2013 Jensen was appointed Minister of Finance as the Progress Party joined a minority coalition government led by the Conservative Party, the party's first ever government participation.<ref>Saleha Mohsin, [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-10-16/norway-names-jensen-finance-minister-after-oil-spending-accord.html \"Norway Names Jensen Finance Minister After Oil Spending Deal\"], ''Bloomberg'', Oct 16, 2013</ref> Jensen's first national budget included proposals of cutting taxes, and spending more of Norway's oil wealth, and she also appointed a committee to consider changes to the 4% [[The budgetary rule|budgetary rule]] of [[Government Pension Fund of Norway|Oil Fund]] spending.<ref>[https://online.wsj.com/articles/norway-to-spend-more-oil-wealth-cut-taxes-1412766630 \"Norway to Spend More Oil Wealth, Cut Taxes\"], ''Wall Street Journal'', Oct. 8, 2014</ref>\n\n==Political views==\n\n===Economy===\nJensen has described her party to be a \"classical liberal party and also a very democratic party\", and that its \"basic main focus areas are individual freedom, individual rights, less state and more individual freedom\", also that the party is \"in favor of more competition instead of less. Because we fight state monopolies because they don't do good for competition, for price levels, for people's ability to choose between different distributors. That's our basic ideology behind the party\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/interview_norway_progress_party_leader_rejects_anti-muslim_label/24279650.html|work=Radio Free Europe|title= Interview: Norwegian Party Leader Rejects 'Anti-Muslim' Label|date=28 July 2011 |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nHaving been called a \"Norwegian Margaret Thatcher\" in the British press, Jensen has said she views former [[British Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]] as one of her \"political heroes\".<ref name=standp/> Considering Thatcher \"a controversial politician who dared to stand for something,\" Jensen has expressed support for [[Thatcherism|Thatcherite]] policies such as \"[[there is no alternative]] (to [[market economy]])\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2009/05/07/nyheter/inneriks/politikk/regjeringen/siv_jensen/6110686/|title=Norges nye jernlady|first=Gunnar|last=Thorenfeldt|date=7 May 2009|work=[[Dagbladet]]|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\n[[File:S_Jensen_02.jpg|thumb|left|220px]]\n[[File:Sivjensenogfpu.jpg|thumb|Siv Jensen speaking before a [[Progress Party\u2019s Youth (Norway)|Progress Party\u2019s Youth]] summer camp.]]\nJensen is a staunch supporter of [[Israel]], and has stated that she is \"not afraid to defend Israel's right to defend itself.\" She visited the Israeli city of [[Sderot]] in the summer of 2008 and experienced [[Hamas]] bombing first hand, forcing her and her company to run for the air-raid shelter. She strongly opposed the Norwegian government's decision to recognise Hamas as she holds that \"you don't negotiate with terrorists, you just don't.\"<ref name=standp>{{cite news|url=http://www.standpointmag.co.uk/node/692/full|title=A Norwegian Thatcher?|work=[[Standpoint (magazine)|Standpoint]]|date=December 2008|authorlink=Bruce Bawer|first=Bruce|last=Bawer|accessdate=21 December 2010}}</ref> Jensen has in addition advocated [[Positions on Jerusalem|moving the Norwegian embassy in Israel]] from [[Tel Aviv]] to [[Jerusalem]], while also being open to accepting a future recognition of a [[State of Palestine|Palestinian state]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=529145|work=[[Verdens Gang]] (NTB)|date=27 August 2008|title=Jensen vil flytte norsk ambassade til Jerusalem|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, in light of the [[Gaza War (2008\u201309)|Gaza War]], she held an appeal at a demonstration called \"Let Israel live\" in support of Israel in Oslo. The Progress Party's general Israel-policy, supported by the appearance at the demonstration by Jensen and the fact that [[Christian Democratic Party (Norway)|Christian Democratic Party]] leader [[Dagfinn H\u00f8ybr\u00e5ten]] had not joined the demonstration, resulted in many Christian Democratic voters turning to the Progress Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tv2nyhetene.no/innenriks/politikk/valg09/-israels-krigfoering-var-ogsaa-terror-2884507.html|title=- Israels krigf\u00f8ring var ogs\u00e5 terror|work=[[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]]|date=1 September 2009|first=Eivind|last=Fondenes|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Soon after, the [[Norwegian Police Security Service]] (PST) went public, fearing that Jensen might be the target of attacks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=539656|title=Politiet frykter angrep p\u00e5 Siv Jensen |work=[[Verdens Gang]]|date=8 January 2009|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> During the speech, which was held amid the [[2008\u201309 Oslo riots]], Jensen and pro-Israel demonstrators were suddenly attacked by violent rioters throwing rocks, and Jensen was forced to leave the podium.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/midtosten/artikkel.php?artid=545854 |title=Politiet bruker t\u00e5regass mot demonstranter  |work=Verdens Gang |date=8 January 2009 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\n===Radical Islam===\nIn February 2009, Jensen held a speech where she warned about what she called a \"sneaking Islamisation\" (''snikislamisering'') of Norway on the background of a public debate about allowing [[hijab]] as part of the police uniform, and demands from Muslim groups of Muslim-only education and special food in prisons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2009/02/21/nyheter/politikk/innenriks/frp/siv_jensen/4966977/|title=Siv Jensen advarer mot snikislamisering|work=[[Dagbladet]]|date=21 February 2009|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> The speech turned out to be highly controversial in the other parties.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=547178|title=Vil stenge Siv ute fra innvandringsdebatten|work=[[Verdens Gang]]|date=23 February 2009|first=Kathrine|last=Hammerstad|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/1.6493505|title=- Sivs beskrivelse er langt fra sann|work=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=23 February 2009|first1=Bj\u00f8rn|last1=Myklebust|first2=Kristine Grue|last2=Langset|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> She used the immigrant-heavy [[Malm\u00f6]], [[Sweden]] city district of [[Roseng\u00e5rd]] to illustrate failed integration policies, claiming that [[Sharia law]] had replaced Swedish law and that emergency staff could not drive into certain areas. The statements proved highly controversial in Sweden, and the Progress Party was invited to a tour around Roseng\u00e5rd by the mayor and police chief of Malm\u00f6, which it accepted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=547220|title=Politisjefen i Roseng\u00e5rd \"arresterer\" Siv Jensen - Svensk lov gjelder i Roseng\u00e5rd|work=[[Verdens Gang]]|date=23 February 2009|first=Bj\u00f8rnar|last=Tommelstad|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagsavisen.no/innenriks/article400282.ece|title=\u00d8nsker Frp velkommen til Roseng\u00e5rd|work=[[Dagsavisen]]|date=24 February 2009|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100809112716/http://www.dagsavisen.no/innenriks/article400282.ece|archivedate=9 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Jensen did however not join the tour herself.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nettavisen.no/innenriks/politikk/article2569815.ece|title=Jensen st\u00e5r over Sverige-tur|work=[[Nettavisen]]|date=9 March 2009|first1=Trond|last1=Lepper\u00f8d|first2=Heidi Schei|last2=Lille\u00e5s|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nFurther, in March 2009, she stated that the fight against [[radical Islam]] \"is the most important fight of our time.\" She said that she, as a classical liberal, would always fight against totalitarian ideas such as [[communism]] and [[nazism]], and that radical Islam \"is a dark and scary ideology.\" She also accused the other parties of being cowardly, ignoring the questions raised by the Progress Party, and claimed that \"it is probably an expression of the fact that they don't understand what's happening in society around them. They close their eyes and try to present themselves as tolerant and liberal, when in fact they are deeply intolerant.\"<ref name=dag23>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2009/03/02/nyheter/innenriks/politikk/siv_jensen/islam/5100011/|title=- Kampen mot radikal islam er v\u00e5r tids viktigste|work=[[Dagbladet]]|first=Arnhild Aass|last=Kristiansen|date=2 March 2009|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Both these controversies resulted in large popular gains for the Progress Party in polls.<ref name=dag23/> In response to an incident in early 2010, where thousands of Muslims demonstrated in Oslo, she changed her claim of a \"sneak-Islamisation\" of Norway, to instead claim that the debate now was of a full-blown [[Islamisation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/article3515805.ece|work=[[Aftenposten]]|title=Frykter \u00e5pen islamisering|date=13 February 2010|first=Gunnar|last=Magnus|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629123913/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/article3515805.ece|archivedate=29 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrk.no/nett-tv/nyheter/spill/verdi/123458/|title=Siv Jensens tordentale|work=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}} (Video clip)</ref> During the demonstration (a response to newspaper ''[[Dagbladet]]'' publishing a [[Muhammad]] cartoon in the context of a news story) Islamist [[Mohyeldeen Mohammad]] had notably \"warned\" of a \"[[September 11 attacks|9/11]]\" or \"[[7 July 2005 London bombings|7/7]]\" in Norway to applause from the crowd.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2010/02/12/nyheter/karikatur/utenriks/politikk/innenriks/10369255/|title=Advarte mot 11. september i Norge|work=[[Dagbladet]]|date=12 February 2010|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\n===Climate change===\nAbout [[climate change]], Jensen said in December 2008 that \"we can see that climate changes are happening, but they have been happening for as long as the world has existed. The question is whether they are man-made or not, or whether they are dangerous or not. Just some 30 years ago, all these scientists said that the world was getting colder, and now they have changed their mind and say that the world is getting warmer. So is that what's happening, or isn't it?\" Regardless, she is largely supportive of expanding and researching into renewable energy production.<ref name=standp/> In January 2010 she attacked the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change|IPCC]], accusing the report from the panel of being based on fraudulent data. She referred to the erroneous statement of [[Himalaya]]n [[glacier]]s melting by 2035, ice melting predictions by [[Al Gore]] and [[Jonas Gahr St\u00f8re]], questions of [[Sampling (statistics)|statistical sampling]], and emails from climate scientists at the [[Climatic Research Unit email incident|Climatic Research Unit]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/article3493769.ece|work=[[Aftenposten]]|title=- Ikke mer snakk om global oppvarming|first=Gunnar Magnus Paul|last=Audestad|date=31 January 2010|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604034803/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/article3493769.ece|archivedate=4 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nBesides three half-sisters,<ref name=p4port>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/p4-portrettet/id303308158|work=[[P4 Radio Hele Norge|P4]]|title=Portrettet: Siv Jensen|date=1 March 2009|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Jensen has one younger brother, businessman Tom Einar Jensen,<ref>{{cite news|last=Online|first=Hegnar|title=Jensen gikk p\u00e5 dagen|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2013/09/13/nyheter/okonomi/hegnarno/agrinos/bohn/29247873/|accessdate=13 September 2013|newspaper=Dagbladet.no|date=13 September 2013|language=Norwegian}}</ref> and one younger sister, Nina Jensen, former CEO of [[World Wide Fund for Nature|WWF]].<ref name=\"storenorske\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=165531|title=Frp-Siv f\u00e5r milj\u00f8kjeft fra lilles\u00f8ster|work=[[Verdens Gang]]|first=Line|last=Torvik|date=27 January 2007|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Norway. Her great-grandmother was the early [[feminist movement|feminist]] [[Betzy Kjelsberg]].<ref name=tu>{{cite news|url=http://www.tu.no/politikk/article187822.ece|title=FrP-Siv vil lykkes innen 2013|work=[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]|first=Tormod|last=Haugstad|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian|date=18 November 2008}}</ref> Although she was once engaged, Jensen has never married.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nilsen|first=Per Ingar|title=Siv Jensen snakker ut om bruddet   Br\u00f8t forlovelse med dr\u00f8mmemannen|url=http://www.klikk.no/produkthjemmesider/herogna/article857664.ece|accessdate=14 September 2013|newspaper=Her og N\u00e5|date=23 August 2013|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nJensen has stated to be a \"proud member of the [[Church of Norway]]\", while expressing some personal doubt about certain Christian doctrines. She has criticised church leaders for getting too involved in politics, particularly in regard to some church leaders publicly voicing opposition to Norwegian [[oil drilling]].<ref>[http://e24.no/kommentarer/spaltister/oljesoel-fra-kirken/2937998 \"Oljes\u00f8l fra Kirken\"], ''E24'', 20.02.2009</ref><ref>[http://www.vl.no/2.627/en-varslet-katastrofe-1.61098 \"En varslet katastrofe\"], ''V\u00e5rt Land'', 30.08.2013</ref>\n\nIn 2006, a biography on Siv Jensen was released, written by Martine Aurdal, chief editor of the feminist magazine ''Fett'', later chief editor of the [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] news magazine ''[[Ny Tid]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.klassekampen.no/39923/article/item/null|title=Avviser drahjelp til Frp|work=[[Klassekampen]]|date=4 October 2006|first=Christiane Jordheim|last=Larsen|accessdate=21 December 2010|language=Norwegian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717135407/http://www.klassekampen.no/39923/article/item/null|archivedate=17 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|title=Siv: Portrett av en formann|first=Martine|last=Aurdal|year=2006|publisher=Kagge forlag|location=Oslo}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Carl I. Hagen|Carl Hagen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]]|years=2006\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sigbj\u00f8rn Johnsen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]]|years=2013\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jan Tore Sanner]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Stortinget 2001-2005}}\n{{stortinget 2005-2009}}\n{{Stortinget 2009-2013}}\n{{Stortinget 2013-2017}}\n{{Stortinget 2017-2021}}\n{{Progress Party (Norway)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jensen, Siv}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Norwegian Lutherans]]\n[[Category:Norwegian School of Economics alumni]]\n[[Category:Progress Party (Norway) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Storting]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Norway]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Finance of Norway]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Storting]]\n[[Category:Critics of Islamism]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian women politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Norway]]\n[[Category:Women finance ministers]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo fixing, replaced: Parlimentary \u2192 Parliamentary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siv_Jensen"}
